{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473123"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:04:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:04:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1936"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1936"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.76,0.03,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78331"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1936"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63701"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"963"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30391"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78331"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of central, colicky abdominal pain, relieved by vomiting. His parents report he has not passed stool or flatus for 24 hours. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His abdomen is distended but soft, with hyperactive bowel sounds. An abdominal X-ray confirms small bowel obstruction. His condition does not improve with conservative management. At laparoscopy, a fibrous band is found running from the umbilicus to the ileal mesentery, through which a small bowel loop has herniated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of the small bowel obstruction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Patent processus vaginalis","Omphalomesenteric duct remnant","Gastroschisis","Omphalocele","Idiopathic intussusception"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of central, colicky abdominal pain relieved by vomiting, with abdominal distension and hyperactive bowel sounds, is suggestive of small bowel obstruction in this seven-year-old boy. The finding of a fibrous band running from the umbilicus to the ileal mesentery at laparoscopy is most consistent with an \u003Cstrong\u003Eomphalomesenteric duct remnant\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as the vitelline duct). The omphalomesenteric duct normally connects the primitive gut to the yolk sac and is obliterated by the eighth week of gestation. Failure of this duct to completely obliterate can lead to various abnormalities, including the fibrous band seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epatent processus vaginalis\u003C/strong\u003E would result in an incarcerated indirect inguinal hernia, which is the most common type of hernia in children. However, the findings in this case are not consistent with an inguinal hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroschisis\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital abdominal wall defect lateral to the umbilicus that allows protrusion of abdominal contents, typically presenting in the neonatal period. It would not cause a fibrous band in a seven-year-old child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmphalocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a midline abdominal wall defect with herniation of abdominal contents covered by a membrane. Like gastroschisis, it presents at birth and would not explain the current findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intussusception\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in infants 6-18 months of age and presents with intermittent abdominal pain and \u0027redcurrant jelly\u0027 stools. It would not explain the presence of the fibrous band found at laparoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment involves surgical division of the fibrous band and careful inspection of the bowel for other anomalies, particularly a Meckel\u0027s diverticulum which is commonly associated with omphalomesenteric duct remnants.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Omphalomesenteric duct remnants are a rare cause of small bowel obstruction in children, presenting with fibrous bands from umbilicus to ileum.","Small bowel obstruction in children presents with colicky abdominal pain, vomiting, and absent bowel motions.","Failure of conservative management in bowel obstruction warrants surgical exploration."],"references":["Kuru, S. Meckel\u0027s diverticulum: clinical features, diagnosis and management. Revista Espa\u00f1ola de Enfermedades Digestivas. 2018;110(11):726-732. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30032625/","Elsayes KM, Menias CO, Harvin HJ, Francis IR. Imaging manifestations of Meckel\u0027s diverticulum. AJR Am J Roentgenol. 2007;189(1):81-88. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17579156/","Tanaka A, Fujii T, Katami H, Ishikawa R, Haba R, Shimono R. Omphalomesenteric Ducts and Urachal Remnants: A Retrospective Study and Case Series. Cureus. 2024 Jul 5;16(7):e63877. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11298018/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63701"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1936"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63701"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T12:53:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-07T20:49:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1936"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78331"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"grou